WEBVTT

00:03.128 --> 00:06.166
I'm still having trouble
turning myself into other things.

00:06.340 --> 00:08.796
- Sabrina.
- Oh, sorry.

00:08.967 --> 00:11.720
I was thinking
about Senior Skip Day again.

00:11.887 --> 00:15.589
A snow day with no snow?
A summer day in the middle of spring?

00:15.766 --> 00:18.602
Forget the metaphors. It's another day
we don't have to go to school.

00:18.769 --> 00:21.890
Well, try to focus. I have to pass
the test for my witch's licence.

00:22.397 --> 00:25.518
Right, focus.
Well, try something simple.

00:25.692 --> 00:27.236
Turn yourself into a pomegranate.

00:28.028 --> 00:31.149
Hey, maybe we should go
to the mountains for Senior Skip Day.

00:35.786 --> 00:37.411
DREAMA [IN VOICEOVER]:
<i>Sabrina? Sabrina.</i>

00:37.579 --> 00:39.822
What? Sorry, gotta concentrate.

00:39.998 --> 00:41.328
- Dreama?
DREAMA: Yeah?

00:43.335 --> 00:45.661
I said pomegranate,
not Pomeranian.

00:45.879 --> 00:46.911
[BARKING]

00:47.089 --> 00:48.335
Don't make me get
the rolled-up newspaper.

00:50.000 --> 00:56.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

01:23.375 --> 01:25.203
- Zellie.
- There.

01:25.377 --> 01:27.703
I've just finished reading
everything there is to know

01:27.880 --> 01:29.126
about Other Realm medicine.

01:29.339 --> 01:31.796
Yet you can't name me
three out of the five Marx Brothers.

01:31.967 --> 01:33.759
I was getting bored
with the other sciences.

01:33.927 --> 01:35.126
I want to heal.

01:35.345 --> 01:37.754
Well, you can start
by healing my wardrobe.

01:37.931 --> 01:40.554
- Lend me your red sweater.
- No, you spill.

01:40.767 --> 01:42.428
Even with all this knowledge,

01:42.603 --> 01:45.391
I'm still gonna have to have
some practical hands-on experience.

01:45.564 --> 01:50.061
Please? Do it for the sweater.
I look really cute in it.

01:52.738 --> 01:54.731
Okay, your 15 minutes is up.

01:54.907 --> 01:56.188
Give me back my lung.

01:56.950 --> 02:00.783
- Two more minutes.
- No, I need to go up some stairs.

02:00.996 --> 02:03.037
Fine, but you're not being
very supportive.

02:04.041 --> 02:05.619
Ah! Thank you.

02:05.792 --> 02:08.201
[SNIFFS THEN COUGHS]

02:08.377 --> 02:11.333
Oh! I take it this is your slide.

02:13.800 --> 02:16.553
Okay, as intriguing
as the aptly named Boer War is,

02:16.720 --> 02:18.595
I can't stop thinking
about Senior Skip Day.

02:18.805 --> 02:20.384
Yeah, I know. It's gonna be great.

02:20.557 --> 02:24.093
- What do you wanna do?
- I don't know, maybe go to a park.

02:24.269 --> 02:27.437
Canoes, picnics...

02:28.690 --> 02:30.767
[PLAYING UPBEAT TUNE]

02:35.280 --> 02:37.440
DREAMA: Sabrina.
- What?

02:37.658 --> 02:39.616
What is the answer to whatever

02:39.785 --> 02:42.454
the question is that you asked me.
Am I right?

02:42.621 --> 02:43.653
[BELL RINGS]

02:43.830 --> 02:47.082
- I'm really starting to worry about you.
- I was having super-vivid daydreams.

02:47.251 --> 02:49.540
BRAD: It was the weirdest daydream
I ever had.

02:49.753 --> 02:52.376
You and Sabrina were having a picnic
in the middle of the class.

02:52.548 --> 02:54.625
- And you were wearing seersucker.
- Weird.

02:54.842 --> 02:57.298
Okay, Brad is a witch-hunter
who can turn me into a mouse,

02:57.469 --> 02:59.961
and now he can see my daydreams.

03:00.138 --> 03:02.512
I'm sure it's nothing
to be concerned about.

03:02.683 --> 03:03.763
Gotta go.

03:03.976 --> 03:05.471
Ow! Ow!

03:05.644 --> 03:07.270
And need I say it again: Ow!

03:07.437 --> 03:09.016
Hold still.

03:09.189 --> 03:11.230
Do you wanna borrow my necklace
or don't you?

03:11.400 --> 03:14.271
Obviously, you skipped the chapter
on bedside manner.

03:14.987 --> 03:18.107
Aunt Hilda, Aunt Zelda.

03:18.699 --> 03:19.779
Problem.

03:20.409 --> 03:22.449
Definitely feel a little warm.

03:22.619 --> 03:24.447
Let's see, a temperature,

03:24.621 --> 03:26.948
vivid daydreams
visible to a witch-hunter.

03:27.165 --> 03:29.658
- Having any trouble concentrating?
- Not really.

03:29.835 --> 03:30.998
Aren't puppies great?

03:31.211 --> 03:33.086
I've got an idea.

03:37.259 --> 03:39.668
Oh, don't make me
call Child Services.

03:39.845 --> 03:40.925
Hold on.

03:42.806 --> 03:45.642
Okay. Just hit the lever.

03:47.728 --> 03:49.140
[BELL RINGS]

03:49.521 --> 03:51.764
I knew it. You've got spring fever.

03:52.858 --> 03:56.275
I always wanted to work at a carnival,
but I've got too many teeth.

03:57.070 --> 03:59.527
"Spring fever occurs
when a young witch

03:59.698 --> 04:01.822
is looking particularly forward
to something."

04:02.034 --> 04:04.703
Senior Skip Day. It's tomorrow,
and it's all I can think about.

04:04.912 --> 04:06.241
- Oh, phooey.
- What's the matter?

04:06.413 --> 04:09.534
- I'm not gonna combust, am I?
- No. I don't need to treat you.

04:09.750 --> 04:12.586
"Spring fever will disappear
once the patient has experienced

04:12.753 --> 04:13.868
what she's focused on."

04:14.046 --> 04:16.502
So after you have
your Senior Skip Day, you'll be cured.

04:16.714 --> 04:18.209
But why is Brad
seeing her daydreams?

04:18.382 --> 04:22.252
Well, he's obviously hypersensitive.
Do not do any magic around him.

04:22.471 --> 04:25.177
- No problem. I'll go take a nap.
- Nap at school.

04:25.349 --> 04:28.516
Be careful, Hilda.
Do not let her hand touch your fingers.

04:28.685 --> 04:31.224
Spring fever can be very contagious
among witches.

04:31.438 --> 04:32.602
When exactly did Aunt Zelda

04:32.773 --> 04:34.233
- become a doctor?
- This morning.

04:36.401 --> 04:37.861
And that's when I told coach,

04:38.070 --> 04:39.613
"I know they make
your muscles bigger,

04:39.780 --> 04:42.402
but don't steroids also kill you?"

04:42.616 --> 04:44.775
What is that man think--?
Oh, ice cream.

04:45.911 --> 04:47.869
- Are you okay?
- I am now.

04:48.080 --> 04:49.409
Attention, seniors.

04:49.915 --> 04:54.163
In the past, there has been
a tradition called Senior Skip Day,

04:54.336 --> 04:57.089
where teachers look the other way
while students become truants.

04:57.256 --> 04:59.878
Heh-heh.
Well, not on my watch.

05:01.051 --> 05:04.302
Senior Skip Day is hereby cancelled.

05:04.513 --> 05:06.553
[STUDENTS GROAN]

05:06.765 --> 05:09.008
Music to my ears. Ha-ha.

05:09.226 --> 05:12.098
Wait, did he just say
no Senior Skip Day?

05:12.312 --> 05:14.520
But I need Senior Skip Day
to cure me.

05:15.190 --> 05:18.062
And I need it to clean my carburettor.

05:18.902 --> 05:21.275
Mr. Kraft,
you can't cancel Senior Skip Day.

05:21.488 --> 05:24.063
Why? Because you and your
annoyingly perky friends will be sad?

05:24.241 --> 05:27.444
- Well, that's my intent.
- No, because...

05:27.619 --> 05:29.280
Because...

05:30.080 --> 05:32.833
Never in my life have I seen
such deplorable behaviour.

05:33.417 --> 05:36.834
- Or smelled such cheap cologne.
- But...

05:37.004 --> 05:38.084
No.

05:38.297 --> 05:40.456
Not the walk of shame.

05:40.674 --> 05:42.751
[DRUMMING]

05:50.642 --> 05:52.435
I know I was making a point.

05:52.644 --> 05:55.314
Yeah, and I'm sure
the aliens in your dental work

05:55.480 --> 05:56.940
understood it perfectly.

05:57.107 --> 05:58.935
[MOUTHS WORD]

05:59.985 --> 06:01.813
I've gotta get Skip Day back.

06:02.029 --> 06:03.857
No, if you don't lend me
your sunglasses,

06:04.031 --> 06:05.526
I don't lend you my small intestine.

06:05.741 --> 06:09.193
Oh, fine, thwart my attempts to
come up with a spring-fever vaccine.

06:09.411 --> 06:11.986
Spring fever? Horrible stuff.

06:12.206 --> 06:13.535
I had it once during an invasion,

06:13.707 --> 06:16.709
and for the first time in history,
the French won a war.

06:16.919 --> 06:18.295
And poor Sabrina has it now.

06:18.504 --> 06:20.960
Oh, no,
that means it's in the house.

06:23.383 --> 06:25.009
[MUFFLED] Gah?
- There.

06:25.177 --> 06:26.637
You're alone, you're germ-free,

06:26.845 --> 06:28.886
and the plastic lining
muffles your complaints.

06:29.097 --> 06:32.052
I don't care for the echo.

06:32.518 --> 06:33.550
Come on, seniors.

06:33.727 --> 06:36.302
If we all stick together,
we can help get Senior Skip Day back.

06:36.772 --> 06:37.852
Back.

06:38.023 --> 06:40.692
[SINGING]
<i>Bring back my Bonnie to me, to me</i>

06:40.859 --> 06:41.939
<i>Bring back--</i>

06:42.110 --> 06:43.855
HARVEY: Sabrina?
- Yeah?

06:44.029 --> 06:46.782
I've got good news.
I was just talking to Joey Slotnick.

06:47.366 --> 06:49.525
The big kid
who was a senior last year too.

06:49.701 --> 06:51.494
The one who still enjoys <i>Babar?</i>

06:51.703 --> 06:54.907
Well, he said that principals always
come out against Senior Skip Day.

06:55.082 --> 06:56.577
It's for the record.

06:56.750 --> 07:00.001
Their lips say no,
but their arms and legs...

07:00.170 --> 07:03.256
I forget how it goes,
but they really do want us to skip.

07:03.465 --> 07:06.503
Thank you.
This means I can be cured.

07:06.677 --> 07:10.213
Hey, look at the ceiling tiles.
Don't they make neat patterns?

07:12.474 --> 07:15.013
She does enjoy her life.

07:15.227 --> 07:16.770
Dear diary,

07:16.937 --> 07:20.022
as I complete hour one
of my new life in a bubble,

07:20.190 --> 07:22.978
I realise
it's the little things I miss most.

07:23.151 --> 07:27.779
Dandelions, sunsets,
the smell of bacon in the morning.

07:27.948 --> 07:30.155
Hmm. Speaking of bacon,
I wonder if can I get one

07:30.325 --> 07:33.660
of those George Foreman Mean Lean
Grilling Machines in here.

07:35.873 --> 07:37.950
Have you finished your part
of our history project?

07:38.125 --> 07:39.953
- We need to put them together.
- I'm trying,

07:40.127 --> 07:42.500
but I'm having trouble concentrating.

07:44.298 --> 07:46.624
Greetings and salutations, Sabrina.

07:46.800 --> 07:47.880
I'm the Homework Elf.

07:48.594 --> 07:50.137
You can play to your heart's content,

07:50.304 --> 07:53.389
and when you come back,
I'll have done your project for you.

07:53.557 --> 07:55.716
And I'll have cobbled you
some new shoes.

07:55.934 --> 07:57.015
Italian leather?

07:57.186 --> 07:59.594
DREAMA:
Sabrina? Sabrina.

07:59.813 --> 08:03.016
You're getting worse.
Our project is due this afternoon.

08:03.192 --> 08:04.687
You could use a little spring fever.

08:06.945 --> 08:08.061
What was I saying?

08:08.280 --> 08:10.737
That you would be quiet,
just until Senior Skip Day.

08:11.700 --> 08:13.444
All right, attention, seniors. Ahem.

08:13.619 --> 08:15.778
Just in case any of you thought
I was bluffing,

08:16.455 --> 08:19.291
I will make sure
that any senior missing from school

08:19.458 --> 08:22.828
on Senior Skip Day
will spend the next four years

08:23.003 --> 08:26.338
celebrating College Skip Day.

08:27.049 --> 08:30.335
Oh, no, no Senior Skip Day?
I just gave Dreama spring fever.

08:30.552 --> 08:32.260
I'm turning Mr. Kraft into a toad.

08:32.471 --> 08:35.140
- You can't do magic here.
- Why not? We're in the Other Realm.

08:35.599 --> 08:39.051
Okay, you've passed daydreams
and gone directly to delusional.

08:39.227 --> 08:41.683
No. And now there's no
Senior Skip Day to save you.

08:41.855 --> 08:44.810
Okay, listen.
Stay here. Don't do magic.

08:44.983 --> 08:46.776
I gotta go call my aunt.

08:50.322 --> 08:51.948
[RINGS]

08:52.115 --> 08:54.987
Hello? Hello?

08:55.160 --> 08:56.442
You're gonna have to speak up.

08:58.163 --> 08:59.872
Zelda, is that my ear?

09:00.541 --> 09:02.534
I'm almost done with it.
I'll bring it right back.

09:02.751 --> 09:04.163
[LOUDLY]
Can you hear me now?

09:04.378 --> 09:06.917
Miss Spellman,
the strange mole-like creatures

09:07.089 --> 09:09.379
who live in the centre
of the Earth can hear you.

09:11.885 --> 09:14.377
The next time you take
someone's appendage, ask.

09:14.596 --> 09:16.424
SABRINA: <i>Can you hear me now?</i>
- Oh!

09:16.598 --> 09:19.600
Don't scream, dear.
I'll be right there.

09:20.435 --> 09:22.928
Oh, cool, you pierced it.

09:23.438 --> 09:25.598
[NORMAL VOICE]
Ah. Finally, I can relax.

09:26.483 --> 09:28.192
Dreama!

09:28.652 --> 09:30.859
You stay here
and keep an eye on Dreama.

09:31.071 --> 09:32.531
I'll go get Skip Day back.

09:33.198 --> 09:34.658
Thanks, Aunt Zelda.

09:34.825 --> 09:37.696
Okay. Now, I'm gonna keep
my eye on you.

09:37.870 --> 09:39.947
Hey, look how weird
my knuckles are.

09:41.748 --> 09:42.829
But, Mr. Kraft--

09:43.000 --> 09:45.243
The more people try to persuade me
to be lenient

09:45.419 --> 09:47.459
about Senior Skip Day,
the madder I get.

09:47.671 --> 09:50.128
- But--
- I am very passionate about this issue.

09:50.340 --> 09:52.381
And I will not relent.

09:54.136 --> 09:56.592
Willard,
let the kids have their Skip Day.

09:56.805 --> 09:58.051
Okay.

09:58.265 --> 10:00.223
And why do these walls
feel so cool?

10:00.392 --> 10:04.473
KRAFT [OVER P.A.]: <i>Attention,
seniors, Skip Day is back on.</i>

10:04.646 --> 10:06.723
Aunt Zelda did it.

10:07.441 --> 10:10.478
Wasn't there someone sitting here
a second ago? Dreama.

10:10.694 --> 10:12.023
I'm thirsty.

10:15.741 --> 10:17.236
Was that water fountain
always there?

10:18.410 --> 10:19.526
You're a freak girl.

10:19.703 --> 10:22.906
I swear, Dreama,
sometimes I think you're a witch.

10:23.081 --> 10:25.371
Oh, no. A witch-hunter
said the words "you're a witch"?

10:26.043 --> 10:28.036
And you haven't turned
into a mouse.

10:28.212 --> 10:29.623
Finally, things are going well.

10:30.672 --> 10:31.705
[DREAMA SQUEAKS]

10:31.882 --> 10:34.255
Yep, straight to well
in a handbag.

10:40.265 --> 10:41.464
Aunt Hilda, Aunt Zelda?

10:41.642 --> 10:44.098
- I'm not bending any whiskers, am I?
ZELDA: What, dear?

10:44.311 --> 10:46.554
Brad turned Dreama into a mouse
and it's all my fault.

10:46.772 --> 10:49.264
And I thought you
making me allergic to oxygen was bad.

10:49.441 --> 10:51.518
Oh, let it go.
I made you an antihistamine.

10:51.735 --> 10:54.357
Will you two focus? Hey, maybe
we should paint this room pink.

10:54.530 --> 10:56.523
- I think I might be able to help.
- Really?

10:56.698 --> 10:58.858
- You don't mean buy a cage, do you?
- No.

10:59.034 --> 11:01.407
See, I've been forming a theory
about witch-hunting genes

11:01.578 --> 11:02.777
based on my medical books.

11:02.996 --> 11:05.239
If we can remove Brad's gene,
we can break the spell

11:05.415 --> 11:06.531
and turn Dreama back.

11:06.750 --> 11:10.085
Bear in mind, Zelda's been practising
medicine for an entire day.

11:10.295 --> 11:11.376
But there's a catch.

11:11.547 --> 11:13.873
See, the gene can only be extracted
during the hour

11:14.049 --> 11:16.506
right after a witch-hunter
has turned someone into a mouse.

11:16.718 --> 11:17.882
So we don't have much time.

11:19.763 --> 11:22.255
- See?
- Either that or our cookies are done.

11:23.183 --> 11:25.141
I suggest
you get Brad over here now.

11:25.352 --> 11:27.511
Oh, good. I get all the easy stuff.

11:27.729 --> 11:29.806
Don't worry, Dreama.
We're going to help you.

11:29.982 --> 11:31.810
I'm filled with compassion
for her situation,

11:31.984 --> 11:33.894
but let's get
this filthy vermin out of here.

11:35.904 --> 11:36.937
[GASPS]

11:37.114 --> 11:39.107
What's this? A mouse?

11:39.283 --> 11:40.363
Let's see.

11:40.534 --> 11:43.203
I can leave the bubble,
risk contamination

11:43.370 --> 11:45.198
and have a mouse to play with.

11:45.372 --> 11:50.118
Or I can stay in the bubble,
be healthy... Too complicated.

11:50.294 --> 11:51.326
[SNORES]

11:53.881 --> 11:56.040
Hi, Brad.
Wanna come over to my house?

11:56.758 --> 11:59.132
- Why?
- Why? Why not?

11:59.303 --> 12:00.964
Aren't mushrooms gross?

12:01.180 --> 12:03.802
- You're weird.
- Yeah, you're right, I am weird.

12:04.016 --> 12:05.844
And you should come see
my weird house.

12:06.059 --> 12:07.471
Leave me alone, woman.

12:09.062 --> 12:11.554
- Harvey, I need your help.
- Sure, what is it?

12:11.773 --> 12:12.854
I need...

12:13.025 --> 12:14.105
I...

12:14.276 --> 12:15.855
You are really cute.

12:16.069 --> 12:17.233
You need to compliment me?

12:17.446 --> 12:19.605
No. I need you to help me
get Brad over to my house.

12:19.781 --> 12:21.111
Please don't ask any questions.

12:21.283 --> 12:24.071
If you love me, you'll get him there.
And I'll explain it all later.

12:24.286 --> 12:25.567
- Okay.
- Thanks, Harvey Kinkle.

12:25.746 --> 12:28.036
You're a lifesaver, literally. Ooh.

12:28.207 --> 12:30.781
A Life Saver.
That would be really good right now.

12:32.961 --> 12:34.457
Women.

12:34.671 --> 12:35.704
[CLOCK TICKING]

12:35.881 --> 12:37.376
[HILDA YAWNS]

12:38.258 --> 12:39.718
Okay, I've checked everything over.

12:39.885 --> 12:43.006
And even though my plan
is extremely complicated and difficult,

12:43.180 --> 12:44.675
I really think it'll work.

12:44.848 --> 12:48.135
- Hilda, have you boiled the water?
- I'm so tired.

12:48.310 --> 12:50.469
Do you have an antidote
for your antihistamine?

12:52.356 --> 12:53.685
Where are Harvey and Brad?

12:54.608 --> 12:57.100
Oh, what's the difference
between culottes and gauchos?

12:57.277 --> 12:58.310
[DOORBELL RINGS]

12:58.487 --> 13:00.030
They're here.

13:01.240 --> 13:02.818
HARVEY:
Hey, Sabrina. Um...

13:02.991 --> 13:06.860
Brad's here to see your big-screen TV
with the sports-only channels.

13:07.037 --> 13:08.829
- Where is this baby?
- It's right this way.

13:08.997 --> 13:11.572
I'll explain later. Love you, bye.

13:12.793 --> 13:15.499
I wonder if I should be suspicious.

13:17.005 --> 13:18.631
Nice to see you, Brad. Gum?

13:18.841 --> 13:20.419
No. Kinkle said
there was a big-screen.

13:20.634 --> 13:23.422
Yes. But first, gum, then TV.

13:23.637 --> 13:26.343
Don't worry. It's magical gum
so he can't say we're witches.

13:27.224 --> 13:28.256
[THUD]

13:28.433 --> 13:29.929
It's also a quick-acting anaesthetic.

13:30.394 --> 13:32.103
Perfect. Now for the operation.

13:32.312 --> 13:35.148
Operation. I love that game.

13:35.607 --> 13:37.684
[BUZZING]

13:38.193 --> 13:42.406
This is a very delicate procedure
and I will need your full cooperation.

13:43.156 --> 13:45.031
How about a song?

13:45.242 --> 13:47.200
We'll need a lot of electricity.

13:47.369 --> 13:49.908
There. I'm brewing a storm.
It should be here just in time.

13:50.080 --> 13:51.362
[RUMBLING]

13:51.540 --> 13:53.498
It won't be long now, Dreama.

13:53.709 --> 13:56.248
Could you hold my eyelids open
while I make some black coffee?

13:56.461 --> 13:59.036
Quiet. This must be done precisely.

14:04.845 --> 14:06.221
Mop.

14:06.388 --> 14:07.931
I am not a scullery maid.

14:08.140 --> 14:10.264
My brow.

14:16.899 --> 14:18.180
[DOORBELL RINGS,
KNOCK ON DOOR]

14:18.358 --> 14:19.770
KRAFT: Zoo Zoo.
- It's Mr. Kraft.

14:19.943 --> 14:21.189
I'll get rid of him.

14:21.695 --> 14:23.439
Quickly.

14:23.864 --> 14:25.324
You know what we don't have a lot?

14:25.490 --> 14:27.199
Fritters.

14:28.660 --> 14:31.413
Zelda, we need to talk.

14:31.580 --> 14:32.744
We need--

14:32.956 --> 14:36.872
- What are you wearing?
- Oh, you mean this?

14:37.044 --> 14:41.707
We are big fans of <i>ER</i> around here,
and we're playing the home version.

14:41.882 --> 14:45.334
- So maybe we should talk later.
- No, no, no, we need to talk now.

14:47.387 --> 14:50.306
- What's the problem?
- Senior Skip Day.

14:50.891 --> 14:53.300
Now, you made an excellent argument
for reinstating it,

14:53.477 --> 14:57.096
and I was swayed by it
and your persistent begging.

14:57.272 --> 15:01.401
- I don't want them to have one.
- But it's a life-or-death situation.

15:01.568 --> 15:03.063
Sabrina has got to have her senior--

15:03.237 --> 15:07.615
I mean, all the kids
would really enjoy a break.

15:07.783 --> 15:11.069
But cancelling it was gonna be
my mark on Westbridge.

15:11.245 --> 15:13.037
Principal Brown
was there for integration.

15:13.205 --> 15:14.486
I was gonna be there for this.

15:14.665 --> 15:15.946
[CLEARS THROAT]

15:16.124 --> 15:19.043
- Uh-- Excuse me for just a second.
KRAFT: Just--

15:19.753 --> 15:21.129
Let him cancel Senior Skip Day.

15:21.338 --> 15:22.964
You'll never get rid of spring fever.

15:23.173 --> 15:24.633
- You'll keep daydreaming.
- I know,

15:24.800 --> 15:27.588
but Dreama's more important
than whether or not I function again.

15:27.761 --> 15:30.384
I don't wanna spend the next
hundred years changing cedar chips.

15:30.597 --> 15:32.805
You're right.
The kids don't need a skip day.

15:33.016 --> 15:35.425
I think you should work
on getting rid of weekends.

15:35.894 --> 15:37.389
KRAFT:
Okay, okay.

15:37.604 --> 15:40.227
I just hope we can feel close again.

15:40.399 --> 15:41.728
[THUNDER CRASHING,
KRAFT SQUEALS]

15:41.900 --> 15:43.443
Hold me.

15:43.610 --> 15:44.691
Poor dear.

15:44.903 --> 15:46.185
Got to go.

15:47.155 --> 15:48.781
- There's your car. Run.
- Uh-huh.

15:48.949 --> 15:52.699
Yeah. Boy, I picked a heck of a time
to wear my steel-toed shoes.

15:52.911 --> 15:55.201
At last,
and we still got some time left.

15:55.414 --> 15:57.573
[THUNDER CRASHING]

15:58.041 --> 16:00.830
Hungry.

16:01.003 --> 16:03.127
Hello?

16:03.630 --> 16:07.581
Guess I'm gonna have to search
my gums for food particles again.

16:07.759 --> 16:09.753
What could they be doing
that's so important

16:09.928 --> 16:12.551
they forgot to feed
the cat in the bubble?

16:12.764 --> 16:14.557
- Zellie?
- Speak to me.

16:14.766 --> 16:16.511
I'm okay.

16:17.728 --> 16:18.974
My fillings are a little hot,

16:19.146 --> 16:22.064
- but I'm fine.
- This may sound a little callus,

16:22.232 --> 16:25.104
what with you still smouldering,
but you have a witch-hunter in preop.

16:25.319 --> 16:28.071
Oh, I can't touch Brad.
I'll electrocute the mortal.

16:28.655 --> 16:30.732
Touch me. Maybe it'll perk me up.

16:31.283 --> 16:32.909
I'm so sorry, Sabrina.

16:33.076 --> 16:35.117
I should be fine in an hour or so.

16:35.329 --> 16:37.655
Maybe if we get Dreama
one of those little hamster wheels,

16:37.831 --> 16:40.039
she'll start to adjust to life
as a mouse.

16:40.250 --> 16:41.330
No.

16:41.502 --> 16:42.617
I have an idea.

16:43.378 --> 16:44.459
Brilliant, Sabrina.

16:44.630 --> 16:47.501
With all this electricity,
I'll make an excellent transformer.

16:48.050 --> 16:50.589
I've always had a yen
to groom a poodle.

16:50.761 --> 16:53.004
Hilda, with Sabrina unable to focus,

16:53.180 --> 16:55.257
you're going to have
to perform the operation.

16:55.474 --> 16:57.052
Normally,
I'd find a way to weasel out,

16:57.226 --> 16:59.433
but there's too much at stake.

16:59.603 --> 17:00.849
- I'll do it.
- Great.

17:01.021 --> 17:02.765
Let's get going.

17:02.981 --> 17:04.525
Before your medication kicks in.

17:05.192 --> 17:07.020
Keep it down.
I've got a good stare going.

17:07.236 --> 17:08.612
Focus, honey, focus.

17:09.238 --> 17:10.353
You're our only hope.

17:10.571 --> 17:13.574
- You've got to operate on Brad.
- Right.

17:15.202 --> 17:20.280
Now, you've got to place the electrodes
in the precise spots in a precise order.

17:22.876 --> 17:24.621
[GIGGLING]

17:24.795 --> 17:26.670
- Sorry.
- Place the first one

17:26.839 --> 17:28.998
just above his left eye.

17:31.260 --> 17:32.340
Piece of cake.

17:32.553 --> 17:35.887
Now, the second one goes between
his index finger and his thumb

17:36.056 --> 17:37.432
without touching his palm.

17:37.641 --> 17:39.682
I'm all over it.

17:40.185 --> 17:43.306
ZELDA:
Slowly, slowly.

17:43.480 --> 17:45.189
Not that slowly.

17:45.357 --> 17:47.315
Sabrina.

17:48.777 --> 17:49.809
Whee.

17:49.987 --> 17:51.861
If you tilt your head back,
it's a real rush.

17:52.614 --> 17:55.023
Hey, it's the girl whose friend
got turned into a mouse.

17:55.200 --> 17:56.364
Shouldn't you be working?

17:57.744 --> 17:59.868
Oh, dear, we've lost her.

18:00.956 --> 18:02.451
Actually, we've lost everyone.

18:03.208 --> 18:04.585
I'm talking to myself, aren't I?

18:05.711 --> 18:09.211
I've gotta stay focused for Dreama.
I've got a job to do.

18:09.381 --> 18:11.671
- What's this?
- Just put it right there.

18:14.011 --> 18:16.633
Good, good. Now, the last one
goes on Brad's tongue.

18:17.681 --> 18:19.093
- Gross.
- Do it.

18:22.603 --> 18:25.474
Bing, bang, boom. Give me another
task before I'm as unfocused

18:25.647 --> 18:27.392
as a camera
pointed at Cybill Shepherd.

18:27.608 --> 18:29.067
Last step. Pull the switch.

18:31.069 --> 18:33.146
[ELECTRICITY BUZZING]

18:36.992 --> 18:39.033
- It didn't work.
- You got it, look.

18:41.580 --> 18:45.365
The witch-hunter gene
is a tiny pair of blue jeans?

18:45.542 --> 18:47.500
Quick. Drop them in the acid wash.

18:48.295 --> 18:50.372
[SIZZLING]

18:52.799 --> 18:54.508
You did it. I'm back.

18:54.718 --> 18:56.048
[TIMER DINGS]

18:57.262 --> 19:00.597
Okay. Hand me the scalpel. Oh.

19:00.766 --> 19:01.965
[THUD]

19:03.727 --> 19:06.682
- Get some rest, Dreama.
- And don't eat too much cheese.

19:06.855 --> 19:08.398
Or your young.

19:08.857 --> 19:10.436
Well, things turned out okay.

19:10.609 --> 19:12.104
Except for these floorboard creases

19:12.277 --> 19:14.152
and the fact
that you still have spring fever.

19:14.321 --> 19:16.445
I'm just glad I did the right thing.

19:16.615 --> 19:19.237
And for what it's worth, I
haven't had any daydreams in a while.

19:19.451 --> 19:20.911
Sabrina, you're cured.

19:21.453 --> 19:23.992
I had a hunch
that if you focused on the operation

19:24.164 --> 19:25.825
and snapped yourself
out of your daydream,

19:25.999 --> 19:27.080
you would cure yourself.

19:27.251 --> 19:28.662
Now you don't need Senior Skip Day

19:28.836 --> 19:30.794
and I have a new item
for my medical paper.

19:33.006 --> 19:35.676
If that speech didn't zone you out,
you're definitely cured.

19:36.176 --> 19:38.300
We have to figure out
whether we can send Brad home.

19:38.512 --> 19:41.004
- Do you think he's ready?
- He shoots, he scores.

19:41.181 --> 19:42.380
[TV PLAYING]

19:42.558 --> 19:44.966
Oh, hat trick. Ha-ha-ha.

19:46.144 --> 19:47.723
Ace.

19:48.230 --> 19:50.140
Knock out.

19:50.482 --> 19:52.357
<i>General Hospital?</i>

19:52.568 --> 19:54.277
Oh, yeah, he's ready.

19:54.444 --> 19:56.771
Let him have some fun.
I mean, since we almost killed him.

19:58.782 --> 20:01.701
You know, you gotta give me points
for getting Brad over to your house.

20:01.869 --> 20:03.032
Major points.

20:03.245 --> 20:05.702
For trusting you,
for not asking any questions.

20:05.914 --> 20:08.074
Big, huge, pendulous points.

20:08.250 --> 20:10.327
- Thanks.
- No, thank you.

20:10.752 --> 20:11.833
So, what's going on?

20:12.588 --> 20:14.166
I just needed
some time alone with Brad

20:14.339 --> 20:16.214
to discuss why he dislikes me.

20:16.383 --> 20:19.835
It wasn't easy, but I have a feeling
things will be getting better.

20:20.053 --> 20:21.134
Really?

20:21.305 --> 20:25.303
That's great
because Brad's really my best friend.

20:27.186 --> 20:29.475
And now that he doesn't have
a witch-hunter gene,

20:29.646 --> 20:31.023
I get to start over with Brad.

20:31.190 --> 20:33.397
- I bet he even likes me.
BRAD: Hey, Spellman.

20:33.901 --> 20:36.737
Karen Ann Quinlan called.
She wants her personality back.

20:37.154 --> 20:38.697
A-ha!

20:39.615 --> 20:42.237
- I forgot to factor in just one thing.
- What's that?

20:42.451 --> 20:43.650
Brad's just a jerk.

20:43.827 --> 20:46.450
But at least now,
we get to do magic on him.

20:46.622 --> 20:47.821
BRAD:
My pants!

20:52.377 --> 20:54.454
Hasn't it been pleasant
around here lately?

20:54.630 --> 20:56.919
- Sort of extra peaceful?
- I know.

20:57.090 --> 20:58.586
What's different?

20:58.759 --> 20:59.791
[GASPS]

20:59.968 --> 21:01.001
[IN UNISON]
Salem.

21:01.178 --> 21:02.210
We forgot all about him.

21:02.387 --> 21:05.804
Oh, no, it's the grasshopper
in the jar all over again.

21:05.974 --> 21:09.225
What?
You said Mitzi joined the circus.

21:10.270 --> 21:13.557
Salem, are you okay? Talk to us.

21:13.774 --> 21:16.645
Oh, please, don't bother me.

21:16.818 --> 21:21.031
I'm trying to set
the world record for grooving.

